\begin_layout Section*
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A conventional utility analysis depends on price information.
 The needs of the consumers and the quality of the commodity needed both
 determine the price of the commodity in the market.
 To study the effect of income, social structure on quality across multiple
 commodity groups, we extend the typical utility analysis to include both
 quality and needs faced by the consumer.
 The needs of the consumers can be proxied with the number of members (age-adjus
ted) in the household (and possibly other available scales) while quality
 can be measured as the portion of budget spent on high vs low-price items.
 With the AIDS model
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DeatonMuellbauerAIDS"

\end_inset

, the measures of needs should appear as the control variables in budget
 share equations while the quality-choices could appear as dependent variables
 (along with budget share).
 This is the approach taken by McKelvey 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "McKelveyQuality2011"

\end_inset

 that we demonstrate in the current analysis.
\end_layout

