\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now describe the regression of marked-price against quantity that we
 use to assimilate the price data from the survey.
 To explain this regression, let's consider an example of the marked prices
 of rice (let's say) for 1 kg, 2kg, 5kg and 10kg in the market.
 A typical set of marked prices could be 4£, 7.5£, 18£ and 35£ respectively.
 The plot would look like the one in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:markedprices"

\end_inset

.
 A linear regression of 
\begin_inset Formula $mp$
\end_inset

 vs 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $mp$
\end_inset

 is the marked price of the item and 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 the quantity consumed) is hardly appropriate.
 As if often the case (not just in this example), the unit-prices are slightly
 less than linear as is shown in the plot of the unit-price corresponding
 to the quantities in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:unitprice"

\end_inset

.
 Since we assume that the consumers face the same prices, we do not attempt
 to match the appropriate price with the quantity consumed by the consumer
 but simply the price of the standard unit of that commodity e.g.
 the price per kg for rice in the current example
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
If we were to really look for a perfect match of prices, then not only the
 quantities consumed but the month of the household interview would also
 need to matched with that of the price recorded.
 The prices are hardly available to such density in consumption surveys.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The regression we use therefore is 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{mp}{q}=\beta\frac{1}{q^{2}}+c$
\end_inset

 (assuming that the marked price is lower than a linear increase - see Figure
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:markedprices"

\end_inset

 - by a factor that itself decreases with increasing 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $mp=aq-b/q$
\end_inset

).
 Since we use the price set 
\begin_inset Formula $q=1$
\end_inset

, the price to be used is simply 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta+c$
\end_inset

 for the regression: 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{mp}{q}=\beta/q^{2}+c$
\end_inset

.
 The regression is run only when more than two prices are available.
 When the regression can't be used a simple median is used as the price
 for such cases
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This does not happen as frequently as one may fear.
 For 2010, only 9 identified regions for just 6 items have less than three
