\begin_layout Section*
Analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An analysis of substitution between quality is not complete without establishing
 what quality means in every category.
 Simply put, we take a price-based view of quality.
 A consumer who buys more of the high-priced item - consumes higher quality.
 This view allows us to see how the demand for quality is distributed across
 the population and varies in response to prices.
 As would be the case for any other item, the demand for quality must also
 conform to the usual demand restrictions i.e.
 the conditions of homogeneity, adding up and non-negativity of the Slutsky
 matrix.
 It could be tempting argue that a consumer also observes a price for quality.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before we delve further into how quality could be represented, we survey
 the various approaches towards quality measurement that have been taken
 in the literature whenever the quantity consumed is available to the researcher.
 The simplest of these approaches to is view the demand for a high-quality
 item as more of the low-cost item .
 This approach strives to obtain an adjustment factor for the demand based
 on the consumption on items(see Griliches 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "GrilichesIndex1971"

\end_inset

 for the theoretical underpinnings with the approach and with measurement
 of quality change).
 Houthakker 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HouthakkerFamilySurvey"

\end_inset

provided a similar formulation where quality was viewed as a separate commodity
 (see Deaton 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DeatonQualityQuantityVariation,DeatonEconConsumer"

\end_inset

).
 With this view, the quantities consumed for two (or more) items within
 a commodity (e.g.
 tea and carbonated drinks under beverages) can be viewed as a quantity
 of a composite good (i.e.
 beverages) along with the value consumed of a quality metric (proportion
 of tea and carbonated drinks).
 In other words, the quantity-price tuples 
\begin_inset Formula $(q_{1},p_{1}),(q_{2},p_{2})...$
\end_inset

 within a commodity could be expressed as a quantity and quality pair i.e.
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $(q_{1},p_{1}),(q_{2},p_{2})...$
\end_inset

, we should have 
\begin_inset Formula $(Q_{G},P_{G}),(\nu_{G},p_{\nu_{G}})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{G},Q_{G}$
\end_inset

 are prices and quantity consumed for a composite good while 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_{G}$
\end_inset

 represents the quality of the good corresponding to the real quantities
 consumed for several items.
 Note that regardless of how the items are aggregated, such a formulations
 always requires the rather stringent aggregation conditions of the composite
 commodity theorem conditions to be met (see Nelson
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "NelsonQualityQuantity"

\end_inset

and Deaton 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DeatonEconConsumer"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In earlier an discussion on status consumption, we have explained how the
 demanded quality could be motivated by status needs.
 While an obvious first step may seem to infer the price of quality (or
 status) in the market., we choose to interpret quality from the substitution
 between the wider commodity groups.
 In doing so, one does not really need the price of quality in the cost-function
 (or the budget share regression) - even though quality is treated as a
 separate commodity.
 This is because we already have the real prices of the items - and a valid
 composite good price (base-price) uniquely determines the price of the
 quality
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Alternately, one could interpret the quality in the market as the gradient
 of price of preferred items (sorted by price or otherwise).
 This too would lead to a formulation equivalent to the aggregation problem.
 Consider for example that for energy, such a gradient would be calculated
 with the price one has to pay to get more of electricity.
 In food, this would be the price one has to pay to get more of meat etc.
 The formulation effectively relies on the basket consumed - and is thus
 equivalent to the composite aggregated method (which in turn relies on
 a composite aggregate price).
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's consider an example to illustrate this better (see Nelson for a more
 detailed theoretical discussion 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "NelsonQualityQuantity"

\end_inset

).
 Let's say we observe the consumption on lamb and chicken within a protein
 commodity with prices observed as 20£, 10£ (resp.) and the quantities consumed
 by the consumer are 1.5kg and 2kg (resp.).
 One approach is to the treat the physical sum of quantities i.e.
 3.5 kg as the quantity of the composite good 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

protein
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 However, it is difficult to argue that the consumers optimise the weight
 of the composite good - rather than comparing the disparate quantities
 of items (see Nelson 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
